00:00:00.830 --> 00:00:03.620
The goal of this video is to
explore some of the concepts,

00:00:03.620 --> 00:00:06.590
or formulas you might see in
a traditional physics class.

00:00:06.590 --> 00:00:09.460
But even more importantly to see
that they're really just common

00:00:09.460 --> 00:00:11.540
sense ideas.

00:00:11.540 --> 00:00:14.000
So let's just start
with a simple example.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:16.100
Let's say that-- and for
the sake of this video

00:00:16.100 --> 00:00:17.947
just so I don't
have to keep saying

00:00:17.947 --> 00:00:19.530
this is the magnitude
of the velocity,

00:00:19.530 --> 00:00:22.029
this is the direction of the
velocity, et cetera, et cetera.

00:00:22.029 --> 00:00:24.870
Let's just assume that if I
have a positive number that it

00:00:24.870 --> 00:00:27.580
means, for example, if I
have a positive velocity,

00:00:27.580 --> 00:00:29.994
it means that I am
going to the right.

00:00:29.994 --> 00:00:32.369
And let's say if I have a
negative number, which we won't

00:00:32.369 --> 00:00:34.987
see in this video, let's assume
that I'm going to the left.

00:00:34.987 --> 00:00:36.820
And that way I can just
write a number down,

00:00:36.820 --> 00:00:38.700
are we're only operating
in one dimension.

00:00:38.700 --> 00:00:40.158
You know that it
is specifying what

00:00:40.158 --> 00:00:41.720
the magnitude and
the direction is.

00:00:41.720 --> 00:00:44.072
If I said the velocity is
five meters per second,

00:00:44.072 --> 00:00:46.030
that means five meters
per second to the right.

00:00:46.030 --> 00:00:48.120
If I say it's negative
five meters per second,

00:00:48.120 --> 00:00:51.480
that means it's five meters
per second to the left.

00:00:51.480 --> 00:00:53.220
Now let's just say
just for simplicity,

00:00:53.220 --> 00:00:57.430
let's just say we start
with an initial velocity,

00:00:57.430 --> 00:00:59.317
of five meters per second.

00:00:59.317 --> 00:01:01.400
And once again, I am
specifying both the magnitude

00:01:01.400 --> 00:01:02.150
and the direction.

00:01:02.150 --> 00:01:05.370
Because of this convention here,
we know it is to the right.

00:01:05.370 --> 00:01:08.050
And let's say that we have
a constant acceleration.

00:01:08.050 --> 00:01:11.010
We have a constant
acceleration at play

00:01:11.010 --> 00:01:14.310
of two meters per
second, per second,

00:01:14.310 --> 00:01:16.730
or two meters per
second squared.

00:01:16.730 --> 00:01:20.470
And once again, since this is
positive, it is to the right.

00:01:20.470 --> 00:01:23.340
And let's say that we
do this for a duration.

00:01:23.340 --> 00:01:25.810
So my change in
time is- let's say

00:01:25.810 --> 00:01:31.560
we do this for a duration
of four-- I'll just use s.

00:01:31.560 --> 00:01:33.520
So I don't use seconds
and then sec, and then

00:01:33.520 --> 00:01:34.580
s in different places.

00:01:34.580 --> 00:01:37.150
So s for this video is seconds.

00:01:37.150 --> 00:01:42.170
So I want to do is think
about how far do we travel.

00:01:42.170 --> 00:01:43.860
Well there's two things.

00:01:43.860 --> 00:01:46.320
How fast are we going
after four seconds,

00:01:46.320 --> 00:01:50.490
and how far have we traveled
over the course of those four

00:01:50.490 --> 00:01:51.610
