00:02:03.490 --> 00:02:07.010
So that is my time axis.

00:02:07.010 --> 00:02:07.940
This is velocity.

00:02:11.050 --> 00:02:13.250
That is my velocity
right over there.

00:02:13.250 --> 00:02:15.890
And I'm starting off at
five meters per second.

00:02:15.890 --> 00:02:18.820
So this is five meters per
second right over here.

00:02:18.820 --> 00:02:23.650
So v i is equal to
five meters per second.

00:02:23.650 --> 00:02:25.530
And then every second
that goes by, I'm

00:02:25.530 --> 00:02:27.380
going two meters
per second faster.

00:02:27.380 --> 00:02:30.060
Because it's two meters
per second, per second.

00:02:30.060 --> 00:02:33.710
So every second that goes
by-- so after one second,

00:02:33.710 --> 00:02:35.740
I'm going to go two
meters per second faster.

00:02:35.740 --> 00:02:36.876
So I'll be at seven.

00:02:36.876 --> 00:02:38.250
Or another way to
think about it,

00:02:38.250 --> 00:02:41.080
is the slope of
this velocity line

00:02:41.080 --> 00:02:42.645
is my constant acceleration.

00:02:42.645 --> 00:02:44.310
Or I have a constant slope here.

00:02:44.310 --> 00:02:48.440
So it might look something
look something like that.

00:02:48.440 --> 00:02:51.290
So what has happened
after four seconds?

00:02:51.290 --> 00:02:53.860
So one, two, three, four.

00:02:53.860 --> 00:02:55.470
So this is my delta t.

00:02:55.470 --> 00:02:58.380
So my final velocity is
going to be right over there.

00:03:02.112 --> 00:03:03.820
I'll write it down
here just because it's

00:03:03.820 --> 00:03:06.080
getting in the way of
this word velocity.

00:03:06.080 --> 00:03:09.830
And so this is v. This
