00:03:09.830 --> 00:03:11.150
And what would it be?

00:03:11.150 --> 00:03:13.690
Well I'm starting at
five meters per second.

00:03:13.690 --> 00:03:15.780
So I'm going to do it
both, using the variables,

00:03:15.780 --> 00:03:17.800
and using the concrete numbers.

00:03:17.800 --> 00:03:21.940
So starting at some
initial velocity.

00:03:21.940 --> 00:03:24.750
The subscript i
says i for initial.

00:03:24.750 --> 00:03:27.720
And then each second
that goes by, I'm

00:03:27.720 --> 00:03:29.830
getting this much faster.

00:03:29.830 --> 00:03:32.470
So if I want to see how
much faster have I gone,

00:03:32.470 --> 00:03:34.640
I multiply the
number of seconds--

00:03:34.640 --> 00:03:37.180
I'll just multiply the
number of seconds that go by,

00:03:37.180 --> 00:03:38.265
times my acceleration.

00:03:42.300 --> 00:03:44.800
And once again, this
right here, I just

00:03:44.800 --> 00:03:46.400
wrote the subscript
c saying that it's

00:03:46.400 --> 00:03:48.120
a constant acceleration.

00:03:48.120 --> 00:03:50.650
And so that will tell
me how fast I've gone.

00:03:50.650 --> 00:03:53.310
If I start at this
point, and I multiply

00:03:53.310 --> 00:03:56.950
the duration times my
slope, I will get this high.

00:03:56.950 --> 00:03:58.475
I will get to my final velocity.

00:04:01.365 --> 00:04:03.455
And just to make it
clear with the numbers,

00:04:03.455 --> 00:04:05.080
