final velocity.

00:04:51.837 --> 00:04:53.170
And I want to take a pause here.

00:04:53.170 --> 00:04:54.961
And you can pause and
think about yourself.

00:04:54.961 --> 00:04:56.710
This hopefully
should be intuitive.

00:04:56.710 --> 00:04:59.780
We were starting at going
five meters per second.

00:04:59.780 --> 00:05:01.590
Every second that
goes by we're going

00:05:01.590 --> 00:05:03.920
to go two meters
per second faster.

00:05:03.920 --> 00:05:06.630
So after one second we will
be at seven meters per second.

00:05:06.630 --> 00:05:09.870
After two seconds we will be
at nine meters per second.

00:05:09.870 --> 00:05:14.142
After three seconds we will
be 11 meters per second.

00:05:14.142 --> 00:05:15.600
And then after four
seconds we will

00:05:15.600 --> 00:05:17.420
be at 13 meters per second.

00:05:17.420 --> 00:05:20.220
So you multiply how much time
passed times acceleration.

00:05:20.220 --> 00:05:22.460
This is how much faster,
we're going to be going.

00:05:22.460 --> 00:05:24.520
If we're already going
five meters per second.

00:05:24.520 --> 00:05:26.220
Five plus how much faster?

00:05:26.220 --> 00:05:28.250
13 meters per second.

00:05:28.250 --> 00:05:34.150
So this right up here
is 13 meters per second.

00:05:34.150 --> 00:05:36.840
So, I'll take a
little pause here.

00:05:36.840 --> 00:05:38.340
Hopefully that's intuitive.

00:05:38.340 --> 00:05:40.090
And the whole point
of that is to show you

00:05:40.090 --> 00:05:42.867
that this formula that you'll
often see in many physics

00:05:42.867 --> 00:05:45.200
books-- It's not just something
that randomly popped out

00:05:45.200 --> 00:05:48.330
of the air-- it just makes
complete common sense.

00:05:48.330 --> 00:05:50.190
Now the next thing
I want to talk about

00:05:50.190 --> 00:05:54.250
